    <prp:abstract>The nature of the emission from the faintest stellar-mass black holes in the ALMA frequency domain is unknown. Radio and mid-IR data allow for different intepretations: (i) a flat spectrum, partially self-absorbed jet that emits all the way from GHz up to mid-IR frequencies, or (ii) a steep-spectrum, optically thin jet at GHz frequencies, plus thermal emission from a cold circumbianry disk at mid-IR frequencies. The former scenario implies that the total power output from quiescent black holes is dominated by the jet, as opposed to the accretion flow. Although this is often assumed to be the case, simply by analogy with higher luminosity systems, no observational confirmation exists. The proposed 100 GHz observations of the nearby quiescent black hole X-ray binary A0620-00 are designed to solve this controversy.  </prp:abstract>
